   <text>
      <body>
         <head>N<hi>otes</hi> to the P<hi>oem</hi> of M<hi>ichael</hi>.</head>
         <div xml:id="note1m">
            <p>
               <hi rend="bold">N<hi rend="small">ote</hi> 1</hi>. Page 159, line 12.
                                   “There’s Richard Bateman,” <lb/>&amp;c. The
                                   Story alluded to here is well known in the country. <lb/>The
                                   Chapel is called Ings Chapel ; and is on the right hand <lb/>side
                                   of the road leading from Kendal to Ambleside.<lb/>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div xml:id="note2m">
            <p>
               <hi rend="bold">N<hi rend="small">ote </hi>2</hi>. Page 162, line 1. “
                                   ———had design’d to <lb/>build a
                                   Sheep-fold.” &amp;c. It may be proper to inform some
                                   rea-<lb/>ders, that a sheep-fold in these mountains is an
                                   unroofed build-<lb/>ing of stone walls with different divisions.
                                   It is generally pla-<lb/>ced by the side of a brook for the
                                   convenience of washing the <lb/>sheep ; but it is also useful as
                                   a shelter for them, and as a place <lb/>to drive them into, to
                                   enable the shepherds conveniently to sin-<lb/>gle out one or more
                                   for any particular purpose.<lb/>
            </p>
         </div>
      </body>
